Ashbourne,Derbyshire,England":"Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cokayne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Cockayne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cockayne","meanings":["English (Midlands and Yorkshire): nickname for a dreamer, from Middle English <i>cokayne</i> ‘cloud-cuckooland’, the name of an imaginary paradise (Old French <i>(pays de) cocaigne</i>, from Middle Low German <i>kōkenje</i>, a diminutive of <i>kōke</i> ‘cake’, since in this land the houses were thought to be made of cake). It may also be a variant of   Cocking   or from the unflattering Middle English nickname <i>cokin</i> (Old French <i>coquin)</i> ‘disreputable person’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":31,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":40,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":75,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Cokayne was born in 1184, in Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England, his father, William de Cokayne, was 32 and his mother, Sarah Fitzaldecinder, was 28. He married Alice d'Aubigny about 1214, in Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1270, in his hometown, at the age of 86, and was buried in Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England."},"et":{"1184–1270":"1184–1270","1188–1298":"1188–1298","1215–1305":"1215–1305","1220–1300":"1220–1300","1153–1242":"1153–1242","1157–1188":